FBIS3-7802 "dreeu039_t_94001" FBIS-EEU-94-039 Document Type:Daily Report 28 Feb 1994 HUNGARY Translating Material From the Hungarian Minority Press 11111111 11111111 Article Type:CSO [Text]Translating material from the press of the Hungarian minorities in Romania, Slovakia, Serbia, and Ukraine presents several difficulties. In the original text, cities and other geographic areas are called by their traditional Hungarian names, which are usually different from the official names used in the majority language. In addition, parties and organizations are often designated by unexpanded acronyms, and it is not even always clear whether these are derived from the Hungarian or from the majority language. Moreover, some designations are politically sensitive due to territorial disputes or historical considerations. FBIS has adopted the following guidelines for handling such material. The guidelines assume that the translator has access to the bilingual list of place names published in Budapest: (MAGYAR NEVE? Hatarokon tuli helysegnev-szotar; Arany Lapok, 1990). Since the Ukrainian section of the book gives the Russian form and is therefore obsolete, a partial Hungarian/Ukrainian list of place names is included below (p.6). In addition, lists of party and organization acronyms are provided. I. Use of Bilingual Place Names and Acronyms Translations should give the majority-language form of place names and organizations that is approved by the Board of Geographic Names (BGN) gazetteer, because this is the internationally recognized form found on maps. At the same time, the source's use of the Hungarian should be indicated because it reflects the original material and may have political implications. The following guidelines address both requirements: 1. In the headline and subslug, use the majority language version of the place or organization (in the latter case, usually an acronym). 2. In the text, use whatever place name or acronym is used in the original. If this is in Hungarian, cross-reference the majority-language version in a bracketed editorial note on its first appearance in the item. 3. As is indicated by the above, the English acronym is not used. Example: Marko Interviewed at UDMR Conference in Oradea Bucharest ROMANIAI MAGYAR SZO in Hungarian 19 Jun 93 p 9 [Interview with Bela Marko, chairman of the Democratic Union of Hungarians in Romania, by Janos Szabo in Oradea; date not given: "Marko on Future Role of UDMR"] [Text] Shortly after his arrival in Nagyvarad [Oradea], Bela Marko, president of the Democratic Union of Hungarians in Romania [RMDSZ--in Romanian, UDMR], gave an interview to our paper. [Szabo] What do you expect the RMDSZ to achieve here in Nagyvarad? [Marko] I hope that we can resolve some of the problems we encountered at last month's session in Kolozsvar [Cluj], where the Hungarian Smallholders Party of Romania [RMK--in Romanian, PMGMR].... II. List of Acronyms The following lists are incomplete but include most of the acronyms used in the Hungarian minority press of these countries in 1993. When possible, both the Hungarian and majority-language acronyms are listed and cross-referenced because the minority press sometimes uses them interchangeably. NOTE: The translation of "szovetseg" and several similar words--translated variously as union, alliance, federation, and association--could not be standardized because of previously established variations in common usage. Romania Hungarian Organizations EMK = Erdelyi Magyar Kezdemenyezes (Transylvanian Hungarian Initiative) FMP = Fuggetlen Magyar Part (Independent Hungarian Party) MAT = Magyar Autonom Tartomany (Hungarian Autonomous Territory--historical ref.) MISZ(SZ) = Magyar Ifjusagi Szervezetek (Szovetsege) (Federation of Hungarian Youth (Organizations) MURE = Magyar Ujsagirok Romaniai Egyesulete (Association of Hungarian Journalists in Romania) PMGMR = RMK (see below) RMDSZ = Romaniai Magyarok Demokratikus Szovetsege (Democratic Union of Hungarians in Romania-- UDMR in Romanian) RMGSZ = Romaniai Magyar Gazdak Egyesulete (Association of Hungarian Farmers in Romania) RMSZ = Romaniai Magyar Szo (Hungarian daily published in Bucharest) RMK = Romaniai Magyar Kisgazdapart (Hungarian Smallholders Party of Romania-- PMGMR in Romanian) RMKDP = Romaniai Magyar Keresztenydemokrata Part (Hungarian Christian Democratic Party of Romania) SZKT = Szovetsegi Kuldottek Tanacsa (Union Council of Delegates) NOTE: This is the supreme decisionmaking body of the RMDSZ. It used to be called the Kuldottek Orszagos Tanacsa--KOT). UDMR = RMDSZ (see above) Romanian Organizations AFDP = Association of Former Political Prisoners AC = Civic Alliance: (Polgari Szovetseg-- PSZ in Hungarian) BUN = National Unity Bloc CD(R) = Democratic Convention (of Romania) (Romaniai) Demokrat ikus Konvencio-- (R)DK in Hungarian) DP(NMF) or DP-NMF = PD(FSN) or PD-FSN (see below) LADO = Human Rights Defense League MER = Ecological Movement of Romania NKDPP = PNTCD (see below) NLP = PNL (see below) NMF = NSF (see below) NPL = New Liberal Party NRP = PRM NSF = National Salvation Front (now PDSR--see below) (Nemzeti Megmentesi Front-- NMF in Hungarian) PAC = Civic Alliance Party (Polgari Szovetseg Part-- PSZP in Hungarian) PDAR = Democratic Agrarian Party of Romania PD(FSN) or PD-FSN = Democratic Party (National Salvation Front) (Demokratikus Part (Nemzeti Megmentesi Front) -- DP(NMF) or DP-NMF PDSR = Social Democracy Party of Romania (formerly NSF) (Romaniai Socialdemokrata Part-- RSZDP in Hungarian) PER = National Ecology Party (merged with MER in 1993) PL-93 = Liberal Party 1993 PNL = National Liberal Party (Nemzeti Liberalis Part -- NLP in Hungarian) PNL-AT = National Liberal Party -- Young Wing PNL-CD = National Liberal Party -- Democratic Convention PNTCD = National Peasant Christian Democratic Party (Nemzeti Paraszt Keresztenydemokrata Part -- NPKDP in Hungarian) PR = Republican Party PRM = Greater Romania (Romania Mare) Party (Nagy Romania Part-- NRP in Hungarian) NOTE: We suggest inserting Romania Mare in parentheses because the party is widely known abroad by its Romanian name. PRNS = Romanian Unity Party for New Society PSDR = Social Democratic Party of Romania (opposition party--1993) (Szocialdemokratikus Part Romaniaban -- SZDPR in Hungarian) PSDT = Traditional Social Democratic Party PSM = Socialist Party of Labor (Szocialista Munkas Part -- SZMP in Hungarian) PSZ = AC (see above) PUNR = Romanian National Unity Party (Roman Nemzeti Egyseg Part -- RNEP in Hungarian) PUR = Romanian Humanist Party PUSD = Party of Social-Democratic Unity RDK = CDR (see above) RNEP = PUNR (see above) RSZDP = PDSR (see above) PSZP = PAC (see above) SZDPR = PSDR (see above) SZMP = PSM (see above) VR = Romanian Hearth (Vatra Romaneasca) NOTE: We suggest inserting Vatra Romaneasca in parentheses because the party is widely known abroad by its Romanian name. It is usally referred to simply as Vatra in the Hungarian press, in which case no translation or expansion is necessary after the first occurrence. Serbia; Rest of Former Yugoslavia Hungarian Organizations DZVM = VMDK (see below) HMDK = Horvatorszagi Magyarok Demokratikus Kozossege (Democratic Community of Hungarians in Croatia) SZMDK = Szloveniai Magyarok Demokratikus Kozossege (Democratic Community of Hungarians in Slovenia) VMDK = Vajdasagi Magyarok Demokratikus Kozossege (Democratic Community of Vojvodina Hungarians -- DZVM in Serbian) VMMSZ = Vajdasagi Magyar Muvelodesi Szovetseg (Hungarian Cultural Association of Vojvodina) Serbian, Other Non-Hungarian Organizations DEPOS = Democratic Movement of Serbia (Szerbiai Demokratikus Mozgalom -- SZDM in Hungarian) DP = DS (see below) DPS = Democratic Party of Socialists of Montenegro DS = Democratic Party (Demokratikus Part -- DP in Hungarian) DSHV = Democratic Union of Croatians in Vojvodina (Vajdasagi Horvatok Demokratikus Szovetsege -- VHDSZ in Hungarian) DSS = Democratic Party of Serbia (Szerb Demokratikus Part -- SZDP in Hungarian) HDK = HDZ (see below) HDZ = Croatian Democratic Community HOS = Croatian Defense Forces HVO = Croatian Defense Council NS = National Party RDSV = Democratic Reform Party of Vojvodina (Vajdasagi Demokratikus Reform Part -- VDRP in Hungarian) RSK = Republic of Serb Krajina SNO = Serbian People's National Renewal Party SPO = Serbian Renewal Movement (Szerb Megujitas Mozgalom -- SZMM in Hungarian) SPS = Socialist Party of Serbia (Szerb Szocialista Part -- SZSZP in Hungarian) SRS = Serbian Radical Party (Szerb Radikalis Part -- SZRP in Hungarian) SZDM = DEPOS (see above) SZDP = DSS (see above) SZMM = SPO (see above) SZRP = SRS (see above) SZSZP = SPS (see above) VDRP = RDSV (see above) VJ = Army of Yugoslavia Slovakia Hungarian Organizations CSEMADOK = Szlovakiai Magyarok Kulturalis Szovetsege (Cultural Association of Hungarians in Slovakia) NOTE: The acronym reflects the organization's original Czech name. The acronym did not change even after Czechoslovakia split, leaving most of the Hungarian minority--and the organization--in Slovakia. CSVFT = Csallokozi Varosok es Falvak Tarsulasa (Association of Town and Villages in Velky Zitny Ostrov) EPM = Egyutteles Politikai Mozgalom (Coexistence Political Movement -- ESW or ESWS in the Slovak press) NOTE: In most cases this organization is referred to simply as Egyutteles, translated Coexistence. ESW or ESWS = EPM (see above) FMK = Fuggetlen Magyar Kezdemenyezes (Independent Hungarian Initiative -- MNI in Slovak) MKDH = MKDM (see below) MKDM = Magyar Keresztenydemokrata Mozgalom (Hungarian Christian Democratic Movement -- MKDH in Slovak) MKDNP = Magyar Keresztenydemokrata Neppart (Hungarian Christian Democratic People's Party) NOTE: appears to be the successor of the MKDM. MLS = MNP (see below) MNI = FMK (see above) MNP = Magyar Neppart (Hungarian People's Party -- MLS in Slovak) MOS = MPP (see below) MPP = Magyar Polgari Part (Hungarian Civic Party -- MOS in Slovak) NOTE: was previously the FMK. Slovak (and Czech) Organizations CTK = Czech Press Agency DSZM = HZDS (see below) HZDS = Movement for Democratic Slovakia (Demokratikus Szlovakia Mozgalom -- DSZM in Hungarian) KDH = Christian Democratic Movement (Keresz tenydemokrata Mozgalom -- KDM in Hungarian) KDM = KDH (see above) KDP = KDS (see below) KDS = Christian Democratic Party (Keresztenydemokrata Part -- KDP in Hungarian) NR = National Council NRSR = National Council of the Slovak Republic (Szlovak Nemzeti Tanacs -- SZNT in Hungarian) ODA = Civic Democratic Alliance (Polgari Demokrata Szovetseg -- PDSZ in Hungarian) ODS = Civic Democratic Party (Polgari Demokrata Part -- PDP in Hungarian) PDP = ODS (see above) PDSZ = ODA (see above) SDSS = Social Democratic Party of Slovakia (Szlovakiai Szocialdemokrata Part -- SZSZDP in Hungarian) SNS = Slovak National Party (Szlovak Nemzeti Part -- SZNP in Hungarian) SR = Slovak Republic (Szlovak Koztarsasag -- SZK in Hungarian) SZSZDP = SDSS (see above) SZK = SR (see above) SZNP = SNS (see above) SZNT = NRSR (see above) TA 5A = Slovak Press Agency Ukraine Hungarian Organizations KMKSZ = Karpataljai Magyarok Kulturalis Szovetsege sometimes varied as Karpataljai Magyar Kulturalis Szovetseg (Cultural Association of Subcarpathian Hungarians) KMPSZ = Karpataljai Magyar Pedagogusszovetseg (Subcarpathian Hungarian Teachers Association) UDMSZ or UMDSZ = Ukrajna Demokratikus Magyar Szovetsege or Ukrajnai Magyar Demokratikus Szoveseg (Democratic Hungarian Union of Ukraine or Hungarian Democratic Union of Ukraine) NOTE: a new organization, probably successor of the KMKSZ, whose name was indefinite as of November 1993. Ukrainian, Other Organizations FAK = Fuggetlen Allamok Kozossege (Commonwealth of Independent States--CIS) KNDL = Karpataljai Nemzetisegek Demokratikus Ligaja (Democratic League of Subcarpathian Minorities) KRT = Karpataljai Ruszinok Tarsasaga (Association of Subcarpathian Ruthenians) MAKS = Megyei Allami Kozigazgatas Sajtoszolgalata (State Administration County Press Service) MSZTE = Megyei Szakszervezeti Tanacs Elnoksege (Executive Committee of the County Trade Union Council) SZSZIUP = Szolidaritas es Szocialis Igazsagossag Ukran Partja (Ukrainian Party of Solidarity and Social Justice) UKBE = Ukrajnai Kereskedelmi Bankok Egyesulete (Association of Ukrainian Commercial Banks) ULT = Ukrajnai Legfelsobb Tanacs (Ukrainian Supreme Council) III. Acronyms (International Organizations) CEC = Euro-Carpathian Region Council FUEV = Federative Union of European Ethnic Groups INTEREG = International Institution for the Rights of Ethnic Groups and Regionalism ITC = International Transylvania Committee KENF = Forum of Central European Ethnic Groups PER = Project for Ethnic Reconciliation SZER = Radio Free Europe (Szabad Europa Radio) IV. Miscellaneous or Difficult Terms Bacska = Backa in Serbo-Croatian (partially Hungarian-inhabited area of northern Serbia) Baranya = Baranja in Serbo-Croatian (partially Hungarian-inhabited area of northern Croatia) Bos = Gabcikovo (Slovak) In keeping with the guidelines on bilingual place names, references to the controversial dam project on the Danube should be rendered as Gabcikovo in headlines and subslugs. In the text, Bos should be retained, with [Gabcikovo] in brackets after the first occurrence. When the reference is to the original joint Slovak-Hungarian project, use Gabcikovo-Nagymaros in headlines and subslugs, retaining Bos-Nagymaros in the text. Treat the first occurrence in the text as follows: Bos [Gabcikovo]-Nagymaros. Csallokoz = Velky Zitny Ostrov (Slovak) (area between the main Danube and its northern branch) Csango = [Partly assimilated Hungarian minority in the Moldavian region of Romania] Untranslatable. Avoid in headlines. Unless the text provides a definition, put the above in brackets after the first occurrence in the text. Delvidek (or delvidek) = ["Southern country"--southern Hungary until 1920, now northern Serbia and Croatia]. Do not translate. Use the original, putting the above in brackets after the first occurrence in the text. Avoid in headlines. Dunantul = [Hungary west of the Danube river] Do not translate as Transdanubia, because it may not be clear whether the region east or west of the Danube is meant. Use the original, putting the above in brackets after the first occurrence in the text. Avoid in headlines. Note that the suffix "tul" (beyond) indicates west of the Danube but east of the the Tisza (see below). Felvidek (or felvidek) = ["Upper country"--northern Hungary until 1920, now Slovakia] Do not translate. Use the original, putting the above in brackets after the first occurrence in the text. Avoid in headlines. Karpatalja = The area of Ukraine on the Western side of the Carpathian mountains. In headlines and subslugs, translate as "Transcarpathia," which reflects the Ukrainian term for the region. However, in the text, translate as Subcarpathia (reflecting the Hungarian original). After the first occurrence of Subcarpathia in the text, put [Ukraine's Transcarpathian region] in brackets. NOTE: When rendering the official majority-language form of a place name, use the Ukrainian form (rather than the Russian as previously in Soviet times). A transliterated list of common place names is appended. Kiralyhagomelleki Reformatus Egyhaz = Kiralyhagomelleki [Pasul Craiului (Oradea)] Reformed Church District. NOTE: Put Romanian term in brackets after the first occurrence only. Magyar = Hungarian Always translate--do not use "Magyars," etc. When the text requires distinguishing between citizens of Hungary and Hungarians living in other countries, qualify as appropriate with a term in brackets: [minority] Hungarians; [ethnic] Hungarians; [emigre] Hungarians. Magyarsag (1) = all Hungarians everywhere. Example: A magyarsag erti Istvan kiralynak a. All Hungarians everywhere understand King Stephen's. Magyarsag (2) = being Hungarian; Hungarian identity. Example: Buszke a magyarsagara. He is proud of being Hungarian. Example: Amerikaban is megorizte a magyarsagat. Even in America, he kept his Hungarian identity. nemzet = nation; people nemzetiseg = ethnic minority; ethnic group; nationality (citizenship) nemzeti kisebbseg = national minority nemzetalkoto elemek = constituent elements of the nation tarsnemzet = co-nation Szekely = Szekler Szekler is the appropriate English translation, but it is obscure. Therefore, avoid in headlines, and put the following in brackets after the first occurrence in the text: [sub-group of the Hungarian minority in the Transylvanian region of Romania]. Tiszantul = [the region of Hungary east of the Tisza river] Do not translate. Use the original, putting the above in brackets after the first occurrence in the text. Avoid in headlines. V. Hungarian/Ukrainian Place-Names ------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |Hungarian |Ukrainian | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |Akli |Klnyove | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |Aknaszlatina |Solotvyno | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |Alsoapsa |Dibrova | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |Alsokalocsa |Kolochava | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |Alsoremete |Nyzhni Remety | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |Alsoverecke |Nyzhni Vorota | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |Badalo |Bodoliv | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |Babakut |Babychi | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |Bene |Dobrosillya | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |Beregardo |Ardove (annexed to Berehove) | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |Beregdeda |Didovo | 